description: Early 17th century, likely back-formation from interloper. Alternatively, directly formed as inter- +‎ lope (“leap, jump”) – literally “to jump in”.

verbs.description: interlope (third-person singular simple present interlopes, present participle interloping, simple past and past participle interloped)

entries.meaning: To intrude, meddle, or trespass in others' affairs.
